(13, 13, 'ws 13.pdf', 'ws_page_13.jpg', 'Jennifer Crawford received the sad news about Lawrence Anthonys death just after she finished writing  her article. One of the last to interview him, she re-wrote before print because everything had changed. I sit staring at a blank Word document glowing on my laptop with the hum of the air conditioner stealing the silence. Ive deleted my story, on deadline. I close my eyes. I see his herd of elephant trum-peting, flinging their rumpled trunks from side to side in distress, kicking up the dust and then slowly, mourn-fully carrying their great bulk up to the lodge to pay their last respects to one of their own  Lawrence Anthony. Oh, his beloved elephants would know of his death. Readers of his book, The Elephant Whisperer would understand this.Lawrence was an extraordinary man whose controversial plans to stop rhino poaching would have made a power-ful difference  and may still. His next book, The Last Rhinos, is due out in weeks. Hollywood has been chasing him to make a movie of The Elephant WhispererIm far from the beauty of Thula Thula Game Reserve, two hours north of Durban, where Id recently been and spent time with Lawrence and his wife Franoise. Id returned. I finished writ-ing the story the very night he died. The early morning call left me shocked and deeply sad. I read through the story Id written after receiving the news. I delete it because it was about Thula Thula, the luxury tents, the chalets around the lodge, the cuisine, the game drives. It seemed trivial now. The story needed to be about Lawrence, only.He was a writer who feared neither the truths that had to be spoken nor the action that needed to be taken when it came to conservation. He was a tall man with a dense beard who wore glasses and a peak cap. He had a gentle way, but was one of the fiercest conservation warriors. His last book, The Last Rhinos is about his efforts in the Congo. In 2007 he went deep into the jungles of the Democratic Republic of Congo to meet with lead-ers of the notorious Lords Resistance Army (LRA) a Ugandan rebel group involved in a twenty-year war with the Ugandan government. He was the first outsider to be granted permission to enter the LRAs secret jungle bases. During his time living with the LRA, he addressed the entire military high command on the need for peace. He reinforced previous agreements reached in Juba Southern Sudan with the politi-cal wing of the LRA to protect the criti-cally endangered northern white rhino and the Congo pygmy giraffe and grant indemnity to conservationists and game rangers in the war zone. This created an international legal precedent as the first time an agreement between warring parties on nature and environmental protection had been sub-mitted as an official document to United Nations sponsored peace talks.Lawrence worked in his own country too, working extensively with communi-ties and their leaders, achieving many conservation milestones and was in the midst of numerous projects.Commenting on this new book, hed said: The new book, yes, well it is going to cause a few problems perhaps. It is controversial, but I operate that way. What has to be done has to be done.The book is due to be released at a gala dinner, also a fund-raiser, where President Jacob Zuma is said to be a guest of honour. At the time of going to press the dinner was still set to be held. The funds were going into anti-rhino poaching. When I asked him what for, specifically he told me:I operate unconventionally. The rhino poaching is riddled with corrup-tion at the highest levels. South Africa has outstanding investigators, they need to be employed, be independent, and the corruption can be cracked. This will change the situation completely. I intend to use the money to fund the investigations and set up an anonymous tip-off line.I dont know who is going to take up the cudgels and assume enough work was in place for it still to happen. Lawrence acted on instinct and with courage. In 2003 at the height of the US invasion of Iraq, he stepped into this war zone to save the animals from the Baghdad Zoo. Wed discussed the legalisation of trade in rhino horn, and of legal hunt-ing. His views were clear. I fully understand that legal hunt-ing has served its conservation pur-pose in creating more land for animals. TheElephant WhispererAUTUMN 2012 '),
(14, 14, 'ws 14.pdf', 'ws_page_14.jpg', 'Please say this when writing to my views. However, we are in a crisis and legal hunting should be suspended immedi-ately until such time the crisis is over.He alluded to the fact that the pres-sure that the suspension of legal hunt-ing would cause, would trigger more people to be involved. He said that, under no circumstances, should South Africa legalise the trade in rhino horn, or sell off stockpiles in order to flood the market.We cant flood the market. What market? The Chinese Mafia? Do you think theyd step aside and allow the local pharmacy to sell ground rhino horn? Never. Legal or not, poachers will not stop. Worse it says we agree the rhino horn has medicinal qualities which it is has none of. This would be a death sentence for rhino.As we drove around Thula Thula, I asked him how he set about writing his books. Did he mean to tell it in story format? How long did it take him plan, then to write? He chuckled and said: I dont know about all that book format stuff. I just sat down and wrote. It took about a year. I have always had lots of help from Graham Spence. What I have done thats helped is reading the best book  the dictionary. I have them all over my house. Every day I read and learn a new word.He underplayed his intellect and achievements. Despite these, and there are many, it was his connection with nature that I found the most remarkable.He was also a gentle man who pursued a deeper connection to nature.  In The Elephant Whisperer he wrote about how the herd of elephant sauntered up to the gate when he returned from a trip to meet him, even though his arrival times were not always the same. Most intrigu-ing was that once, when his flight from Johannesburg was delayed, the elephants had turned around long before reaching the gate.  I loved this part of the book and asked about it. I just wanted to hear it again, from this awesome author.  We all did, all of the friends I was with.Yes, its true. They know where I am wherever I am; there is a spiritual connection. This is possible for all of us. Weve lost touch of the spiritual side of ourselves, with Africa, the earth and animals. We need to reconnect. This communication with the elephants is only one example. I have much anecdo-tal evidence of this connection on the spiritual side of the animals and earth. In the next book I go a deeper into what I mean. Im cautious though because sometimes people find it mumbo jumbo.Mans cultural and traditional links to nature that used to be passed down, generation to generation, have become lost in a sea of civilization, bureaucracy and technology.Lawrence said the need to save the rhinos was about more than the rhinos. Perhaps rhinos are the catalyst to take us to a point that says no more. There is a great sense of proprietorship for the first time amongst many from the Zulu man I spoke to in the village to people all over the world.  The affinity we have for the rhinos, we can bleed it onto lion, elephants and other animals. Maybe we have reached a turning point.I badgered him about the interest from Hollywood. Thered been more than passing interest; thered been huge amounts of US dollars invested in research looking at his first book, Babylons Ark, and The Elephant Whisperer. But, Lawrence said that in his opinion the book that would make the greatest movie would be The Last RhinosHow would you feel about it if a movie was made from this book?It would be the greatest thing pos-sible. It would draw attention on a huge scale.Lawrence leaves behind his wife Franoise, two sons and two grandsons, and millions of people all over the world whove read his books, and seen animals, and especially elephant, in ways they never dreamed possible. Wed had a wonderful time at Thula Thula and I encourage you to go there and enjoy the serenity and find your connection to the earth and animals and write your own story.Farewell Lawrence, you legacy will inspire the conservation warriors.  AUTUMN 2012 10LAWRENCE ANTHONY - The Elephant WhispererPerhaps rhinos are the catalyst to take us to a point that says no more. There is a great sense of proprietorship for the first time amongst many  from the Zulu man I spoke to in the village to people all over the world. Lawrence at Thula Thula, home of the elephant the world came to know through his book, The Elephant Whisperer'),
(15, 15, 'ws 15.pdf', 'ws_page_15.jpg', 'When you were born they threw the mould away. Thank you for the inspiration you were to all of us, especially for the adventures and crazy happenings you brought into our lives and, above all, for your laughter and love. Your passing brought an irreplaceable void in our family but you will always remain in our hearts and minds. Your loving mother and familyLawrence was a free spirit who lived life with passion and wanted to make a difference in this world, for animals and humans alike. He had that unique impact on people and was an inspiration to all with his enthusiastic and non-conformist approach to life. Lawrence touched many hearts and was loved and admired by everyone, and his legacy will live on. Francoise Malby-AnthonyI have been close to the Anthony family for many years. The family has suffered a great loss. Lawrence will be missed by many. We are all proud of what he achieved internationally as a conservationist. People throughout the world respected him. But here in Zululand, we considered him one of our own and one of our greatest. Prince Mangosuthu ButheleziThe cause of saving our planet, our natural habitat, as well as our animal heritage, has suffered a crippling blow with the passing of its champion. I was privileged to have worked with him on some of his projects, such as creating the Royal Zulu Game Park, incorporating Thula Thula up to Mfolozi. He brought nature conservation awareness to the tribal communities of KwaBiyela and KwaMthethwa. It was an incredible achievement. We salute you Lawrence for your untiring efforts to save the planet and its animal heritage. Dr Ben NgubaneThe passing of Lawrence Anthony at so early an age is a great tragedy.  He was man of tremendous courage. He has been deeply engaged in negotiations for the extension of Imfolozi Game Reserve and linking with Mpate. I will miss him dearly as a friend and companion in the never ending struggle for wildlife conservation. Dr Ian PlayerLawrence was a great man. Im saddened by his passing on but will continue with the work we started. We had so many plans; we were going to approach overseas football clubs to join in our Ezemvelo Cup. I hope he rests in peace, he was an icon for all of us in conservation, and his projects will live far beyond his life. We had a shared passion for communities and I promise that I will continue that. Dr Bandile Mkhize, CEO of Ezemvelo KZN WildlifeWere devastated that such a wonderful, talented son of Zululand has passed away, but mercifully spared any suffering, whilst leaving a great legacy for us to lean on. His personal friendship with President Jacob Zuma was an important conduit for the message of Zululand conservation challenges, and in this he will be sorely missed. Hamba Kahle. Zululand Wildlife ForumI cant think of anyone from conservation who was so impressive. I cant think of any politician who does more nation-building. He was so affable and friendly, but there was no mistaking his seriousness. It was a privilege to know Lawrence and to serve with him. He was marvellous. A magnificent legacy. Ian Raper - National President of the Southern Africa Association for the Advancement of Science He was a dear friend. I met him in the Congo where I was working for the United Nations. He was indefatigable. He was a wonderful human being, simple and down to earth, brave and affectionate. I will miss him. May his soul rest in eternal peace forever.  Mujahid Alam, PakistanI always thought of him as indestructible. His enthusiasm was infectious. As concerns his involvement in local communities, he was very genuine. He was old fashioned in that way; his heart was totally in it. Peter Rutsch  Royal Zulu Biosphere. Ive never met anyone so capable of winning unwinnable battles. Lawrence was a get-things-done presence in a realm - conservation - in which passion and science often sink in the cautious currents of inertia and rhetoric. His obdurate sense of justice may be what drove him from one adventure to the next, but it was balanced by a child-like curiosity and mischievousness - as well as an utter disregard for his own limitations. Tom Clynes, author, Michigan, USAIm gutted hes gone but know Im privileged to have been part of his adventures. His personality, drive and vision opened doors that appeared at first to be shut. I hope his enormous legacy will continue to inspire those who have ever had the privilege to have known Lawrence. Brendan Whittington-Jones, EWTHe was not only our boss, but a friend, a mentor and a father-figure.  Our hearts are broken, but we will continue to work along the path he has created for us.  Marissa Lenting, Assistant to Lawrence Anthony Lawrence was a force of nature, a natural force. Compelling in his thinking, lucid in his reasoning, and, that rarest of all qualities, an attentive listener with the ability to recollect events, within their relevant context. Lawrence chose to be involved in matters close to his heart. I salute you, Lawrence Anthony. JP FourieLosing Lawrence has been devastating, personally and professionally. He played a massive roll in my life as a friend and a mentor. The world is poorer without him and he will be missed by people and animals alike. We must continue his work.  Yvette Taylor, Executive Director of The Earth OrganizationYou came, you led, you conquered, when everyone was scared to act, you did what was to be done.You were selfless and full of humanity. You did so much but now you have to rest Mkhulu, your work here is done. I love you, we all love you. Sam Madlala Co-Founder of The Earth Organization-Pietermaritzburg Chapter.We are deeply saddened at the loss of Lawrence Anthony on the eve of launching his book, The Last Rhino. Lawrence was a well-respected northern KZN personality and known to all members of Project Rhino KZN. His untimely death is a devastating loss to South Africas conservation community. Project Rhino KZNACTs Skydive for Rhinos teamsend their deepest condolences to Francoise, Alyson McPhee and the staff at Thula Thula and the Earth Organisation.  Lawrence was a true conservation hero and we will carry on the work to save southern Africas white and black rhinos from the threat of extinction. African Conservation TrustI was recently privileged to have met Lawrence Anthony at Thula Thula.   His compassion, kindness and love of nature shone through.   He will be greatly missed by all and in particular the animals he so dedicatedly loved and bravely championed.  Deepest sympathy to his family.  May grace surround you and may you find comfort in the mighty legacy he left behind. Hamba Kahle.  Rochelle Van Os.Lawrence Anthony was fearless in going to places to rescue wild animals such as in Iraq and taking on a small group of traumatised elephants and rehabilitating them.  He made a great contribution to furthering our knowledge about wildlife. I salute a great conservationist and his untimely passing has left a great void. Drummond DenshamAUTUMN 2012 Lawrence Anthonyfearless conservationist, bestselling author, and owner of Thula Thula Private Game Reserve, touched the lives of many.Here Wildside publishes tributes to Lawrence.Hamba KahleNkosi yezi Ndlovuyase '),
