(38, 38, 'ws 38.pdf', 'ws_page_38.jpg', 'Kosi BayA Magical interludeThe warm seas and abundant marine life of Kosi Bay, near the Mozambican border, are enticing and magical. A wise traveler checks the shoreline and this is where one swims, fishes, launches a boat or lazily listens to the fish eagle calling.  A wide, sturdy boardwalk extends out over the crystal-clear Lake Nhlangi (the third lake in the Kosi system), with two benches at the furthermost point, ideal for sipping sundowners or just reflecting on the days highlights.Down to Kosi MouthEvery Kosi holiday should include a day at the legendary Kosi Mouth. Book a Day Visitor Permit for the following day, and note that only 10 permits are issued per day and are on a first-come-first served basis.  The Mouth is an easy distance of 25km from the Kosi Bay Camp. Follow the sandy road through the access control boom, as it winds down to the estuary past the lake, stopping en route to admire a panoramic view of the Kosi lake system. In the unspoilt calm of the lake below, traditional subsistence farmers harvest their days catch, thankful for the abundance of a full trap, or disheartened by a meager catch. They return day after day, ever hopeful of a meal for their family.Continue down to the Mouth. Paradise stretches before you. Translucent estuarine water shimmer-ing over silvery sands stretches out to the sea beyond. Close to the Mouth, at low tide, a huge tidal pool becomes an aquarium for stranded sea-fish, surging towards the surface in anticipation of the turning tide. Snorkelers floating motionless above them, are awed by their streamlined beauty. If you choose to explore the estuary, wade or snorkel through the crystal clear warm water, wearing strops or crocs on your feet. The area is home to the stonefish (Synanceja verrucosawhich is thought to be the most ven-omous fish in the world. Named for its uncanny ability to camouflage itself, it could easily be mistaken it for a rock with algae growing on it.As the day closes, a palmnut vulture gypohierax angolensis) may settle close-by on an exotic raffia palm, perfect nesting sites, which also serve as their primary food source. The exotic raffia palm has colonized along this coast and the biggest groves are found at Kosi. The tide rules in this part of para-dise, so be aware. With equipment and litter packed away, cast a last glance over this pristine ecosystem and feel proud that it is being conserved for future generations. Head back to camp well before 18h00, when the gates close for the night.Kosi Bay: Ezemvelo KZN Wildlifes Kosi Bay Camp is 420km from Durban and 118km from Josini;Information: For information about permits and boating regulations, con-tact Kosi Bay ofce on 035 5920236How to get there: Co-ordinates 32d4932.99E   29d2313.54STurtle Tours (Nov to March)www.kznwildlife.com AUTUMN 2012 34'),
