(51, 51, 'ws 51.pdf', 'ws_page_51.jpg', 'A Family & Feline FiestaTS A WELCOME PARTY WITH A DIFFERENCE. Besides the lodges staff armed with warm towels to refresh us, a tan and silver-speckled creature sits on a step. Everything in his body posture shows awareness of our arrival. Even before we crunch to a halt on the circular drive, he bounds towards the car.  Bright eyes surrounded by black patches greet us. Its Zulu the Meerkat giving his personal welcome to Woodlands Private Safari Lodge. Not the typical lodgeWoodlands is not the typical safari lodge. For a start the build-ing is not the usual wood and thatch youd expect. Rather, simple architectural lines with generous verandahs indicate its historical origins as a farmhouse. Its authenticity is revealed in the blue grey rough-hewn masonry. Its the stone of Nambiti Private Game Reserve, and firmly rooted in central KwaZulu-Natals geology. Nambiti, situated 25 km east from Ladysmith, is the only Big-5 reserve in this area of KwaZulu-Natal. The reserves 10 000ha var-ies in ecospheres from central savannahs, to open grasslands in the northwest and dense acacia thornveld in the south. Woodlands lodge is among gentle rolling hills of grassland with scatterings of tall acacia. Accompanying the Wildside team to Nambiti is the beautiful Kirsten Dukes, South Africas Miss Earth ambassador. Kirsten has a deep passion for conservation, especially for the preservation of endangered species such as rhino. She has joined us as a guest of Wildside Warriors in support of Project Rhino KZN. However, hav-ing just met, we are all feeling a little reserved. That is, until Zulu breaks the ice and enchants us with his antics.WILDSIDE team and KIRSTEN DUKES, South Africas Miss Earth ambassador,  encounter the WoodlandsPRIVATE SAFARI LODGENAMBITI PRIVATE GAME RESERVEAUTUMN 2012 '),
(52, 52, 'ws 52.pdf', 'ws_page_52.jpg', 'Zulu escorts us up the stairs to the lodges entrance. With the warm reception from Desmond and Elizke Gouws, the lodges general managers, Woodlands is rapidly feeling more home than resort. This feeling of comfort is also reflected in its interior. This is a place where people can feel at ease. As Desmond says about the lodges ethos, Id rather visit a place where I feel at home than feel that if I move a chair its going to mess with the Feng shui. Safari and BattlefieldsA large lounge and dining area leads towards the bar with snooker table. Authentic Battlefield paraphernalia adorn the walls. This treasure trove provides a clue about Woodlands second unusual fea-ture  its the only Battlefield lodge in a Big 5 reserve. Geographically the lodge is perfectly situated to offer guests the combined experi-ence of a safari and the battlefields. With picnic baskets packed, Mike Nel a specialised battlefield guide takes guests on day excur-sions to nearby sites of Roukes Drift, Islandwana, Spioenkop and Blood River. Food, glorious foodElizke informs us high tea is about to be served. Tables are set in the dappled light of a large acacia tree. The expansive lawns are per-fect for children (and Zulu the Meerkat) to explore. As Eliske says, Woodlands is a family orientated lodge. Here kids can run freely around in the gardens and swim. The high tea treats on offer prove to be a foretaste of another outstanding feature of Woodlands  superb cuisine. When Eliske  AUTUMN 2012 48'),
(53, 53, 'ws 53.pdf', 'ws_page_53.jpg', 'AUTUMN 2012 SUPPORTED BY WILDSIDE MAGAZINE & KIRSTEN DUKES'),
(54, 54, 'ws 54.pdf', 'ws_page_54.jpg', 'is asked about the lodges meticulous attention to detail and presentation, she answers, Food is important. You can have stunning accommodation, a fantas-tic game drive but if the food is horrible the whole experience can be spoilt. We believe good food is essential for our guests experience of Woodlands.On a rhino missionAfter a leisurely tea we are sufficiently refreshed to climb back into a vehicle for a game drive. Nambiti is a relatively new reserve, having been successfully developed from an extensive commu-nity land claim. Besides the Big-5, the reserve boasts over 30 mammal species and excellent birding, including being the breeding ground for blue crane, long crested eagle and bald ibis. However on this day, our mission is to see if we can find rhino.Determined to discover them before the days light fades, we wind our way through the reserve. Eventually our elu-sive rhino are spotted in the distance  too far and too late in the day for photographs. Later, with rhino still on everyones minds, we chat to Desmond about Nambitis efforts in preventing poaching. He tells us that reserve man-agement coordinates all conservation aspects at Nambiti. Wildlife specialists, lodge owners and community leaders work together. Nambiti has had good success limit-ing poaching. Desmond believes this is because the reserve is community owned. Community involvement has been key. They are the shareholders and 99% of the staff in the reserve are from the local community. Desmond further explains, With assistance from the Indunas, people real-ised that if they remove game, visitors wont come. The first thing we noticed was that antelope were no longer being taken. With regards to protecting rhino, Desmond says that the reserve is a no-fly zone. He holds the belief that a strong relationship through interaction with the community, pride in the rhino and buy-in from the Indunas is the key. He says,  The voice of an Induna counts far more than any rhino specialist talking to the people. Feline fiestaBreakfast arrives with a bonanza  an introduction to some more unusual members of the Woodlands family. Sky and Storm are three-month old chee-tah cubs. The cubs are the offspring of a female cheetah on the reserve. The mother initially had five cubs. However after hyenas killed two, the mother took one cub and moved to a new den, never returning for the other two. Eventually the folk at Woodlands rescued Sky and Storm and have hand reared them. Even at such a young age, Sky and Storm display the essence of the cheetah persona. They are self-contained, ele-gant and regal. Cheetahs are by nature solitary creatures although this morning they happily seek us out and sit contently purring. The cubs are dignity personified, that is until the entry of Vega a four-month leopard cub. In a blur of spotted fluff, Vega leaps wildly over the coffee table and attacks Sky in mock battle. Cheetah dignity is severely dented as Vega caus-es general mayhem. Finally, Zulu the Meerkat steps into the fray to stamp what he perceives as his authority as leader of the pack. With such unusual family members, clearly Woodlands is not the typical lodge.The Le Sueur Cheetah ProjectRob Le Sueur owns both Woodlands Private Safari Lodge and Nambiti Plains Lodge, a five star African Eco Lodge. As one of the original founders of Nambiti Private Game Reserve, Rob has been intimately involved over the years in its development and conservation. With only about 8 000 to 10 000 cheetahs left worldwide, the Le Sueur Cheetah Project works towards repopulation by breeding and then releasing cubs back into the wild. Cheetahs are highly endangered. They are included on the International Union for Conservation of Nature (IUCN) list of vulnerable species and listed as a threatened species in Appendix I of CITES (Convention on International Trade in Endangered Species). Roughly 2 000 cheetahs are lost every four years worldwide. This is due to three main threats. The first is that cheetahs are at the bottom of the carnivore hierarchy. Other predators, such as lions and hyenas, not only take cheetahs prey but will also kill adults and their cubs. Nambiti has lost 12 cheetahs over the years to lion kills. We ask Desmond why the cheetah just doesnt run away, after all its the fastest land animal with speeds over 100 km/hr. Desmond explains, Cheetahs rely on their camouflage till the last moment. Often its too late, the lions have encir-cled and trapped them.Secondly, human factors threaten the survival of cheetah. Often they are shot because cheetahs hunt live-stock. Destruction of habitat also plays a large role in their declining numbers. Cheetah ideally requires open plains to hunt. However, as Desmond says, Its so much easier to plough up an open plain than to deforest an area. In addition Desmond highlights trade in the East as another factor; The demand in the East for cheetah skin, teeth, skull and bones is a massive problem. Cheetahs skins in Vietnam are regarded as a big commodity. Lastly, cheetahs own gene pool accounts for their rapidly declining num-bers. Sometime during the last ice age an  AUTUM 50'),
(55, 55, 'ws 55.pdf', 'ws_page_55.jpg', 'LE SEURMISS EARTHCHEETHA PROJECTWith only about 8 000 to 10 000 cheetahs left worldwide, the Le Sueur Cheetah Project works towards repopulationAUTUMN 2012 '),
(56, 56, 'ws 56.pdf', 'ws_page_56.jpg', 'extinction of large vertebrates occurred on several continents. The result was cheetahs inbred and the same genes have been transferred from one genera-tion to the next. Today the results of this limited gene pool are sometimes revealed in physical defects. For example, more than 35% of males are sterile. Potential breeding pairsWith such odds stacked against them, the Le Sueur Cheetah Project hopes to give these endangered cats a fighting chance. At present the project has two females and one male adult cheetah. The females are named Shadow and Savannah, and the male is Mikka. The adult cheetahs are currently kept in a 200sqm enclosure just outside the main reserve. An adjacent 1500ha reserve is being prepared for the chee-tahs release, and hopefully successful breeding. The cheetahs have to be kept in isolation. As rescued orphans they havent acquired the instincts to deal with natural enemies such as lions and hyenas. Shadow and Savannah are three-year old twins. Their mother, a Nambiti reserve resident gave birth to them just outside the park. With the stress of relocation the mother abandoned the cubs. De Wildt Cheetah Rehabilitation Center, together with the Endangered Wildlife Trust (EWT), raised the cubs. Before being returned to Nambiti, the cubs were sent to Monate Cheetah Re-wilding Lodge, where they learnt hunting skills and how to survive on their own. Mikka is from the Kalahari and a few months older than the females. Destined for the black market the EWT intervened and rescued him.The introduction of Mikka to the pro-ject allows for potential breeding pairs. The Endangered Wildlife Trust (EWT) checks the genetic profiles to ensure pairs are not too similar. Once the cubs at Woodlands lodge reach maturity they will also join the adult cheetahs in the 1500ha reserve. The projects cheetahs will be free-roaming cats, hunting on their own but protected from lion and hyena. The added advantage is that peo-ple have an opportunity to interact with these extraordinary creatures.Storm and SkyThe sun breaking through clouds becomes the perfect backdrop to Wildsides final experience at Woodlands. The two cheetah cubs Storm and Sky gambol around Kirsten Dukes, as she walks back to the lodge. They have stolen all our hearts and found champi-ons in their cause. As our Miss Earth ambassador says, The whole project truly sparked a fire within my soul. It confirms Kirstens passion for the envi-ronment and conservation.Woodlands is not the typical safari lodge. It is better. As Elizke succinctly sums up guests experience of Woodlands: People leave here as friends.  AUTUM 52Woodlands Private  Safari Lodge: situated in the Nambiti Private Game Reserve 25 km east of Ladysmith and is 3.5 hrs from Jhb, 2.5 hrs from Dbn and 40 mins from Drakensberg.: 5 Large double bedrooms and 1 family room, all en-suite. Fully catered - R1495 ppps.Contact: Tel: +27 (0) 83 377 9340 or 27 (0)83 630 7073 email: woodlands@nambiti.com Website: www.woodlands-lodge.co.zaMiss Earth South Africa is a programme that aims to provide young South African women the platform for making a sustainable difference in combatting the destruction of our natural heritage. The event helps create awareness of our environment, wildlife and the conservation of our natural legacy in South Africa, and ultimately the preservation of Mother Earth.Visit www.missearthsa.co.za '),
