(27, 'No', 'No', 'Competitions', 1, 'rod macleod', 'Win a Mountain Retreat for eight people', 'mountain_retreat.jpg', '530', '', 'Win a three night weekend stay for eight people at the beautiful mountain retreat, Allendale, only 1hr 45 mins from Durban in the uKhahlamba-Drakensberg in the Managers House. ', 'The accommodation is self-catering and the prize does not include any provisions. Terms and conditions as prescribed by Allendale apply and the stay is subject to availability. All arrangements for the stay will be made with Allendale.', 'Enter Competition', '', '2012-08-02 02:13:00', '2012-08-02 02:13:00', 'The Managers House has magnificent views of the valley from its wrap-around veranda. There are  two en-suite bedrooms, two  bedrooms with two single beds each, with a shared bathroom, kitchen, dining room with 8 seater table and lounge with a fireplace for chilly winter evenings.\r\n\r\n<span style="color: #800000;">Question: Whose house do you stay in at Allendale?</span>', ''),
(28, 'No', 'No', 'Competitions', 2, 'rod macleod', 'Two day break away at Walkerbouts Inn Rhodes worth R2000', 'walkerbouts_web.jpg', '530', '', 'Walkerbouts Inn in Rhodes is offering a 2 nights stay for 2 people sharing on a dinner bed and breakfast basis. The prize excludes drinks and activities and terms and conditions apply. Walkerbouts Inn is TGCSA 3 star graded and AA Quality Assured Accommodation in the Eastern Cape Highlands. Activities in the region include hiking trails, nature walks, birding and 4 x4 trails, scenic drives or even pottery and ceramic sculpture lessons at the Inn. ', '', 'Enter Competition', '', '2012-08-02 02:31:00', '2012-08-02 02:31:00', '<span style="color: #800000;">Question: In what town can Walkabouts Inn be found?</span>\r\n<a title="www.walkerbouts.co.za " href="http://www.walkerbouts.co.za" target="_blank">www.walkerbouts.co.za&nbsp;</a>', ''),
(29, 'No', 'No', 'Competitions', 3, 'rod macleod', 'Win one of 5 Books', 'In-Search-of-Africas-Great-Tuskers-lr.jpg', '530', '', 'The book, In Search of Africa’s Great Tuskers, is a celebration of the timeless beauty of untamed Africa – its mountains and deserts, tropical rainforests and endless savannahs. More particularly, though, it is a celebration of Africa’s great tuskers – those bull elephants who are becoming increasingly rare in the twenty-first century, the legendary ‘hundred-pounders’ that were so plentiful in colonial times. Win one of 5 copies of this beautiful book by Johan Marais. ', '', 'Enter Competition', '', '2012-08-02 02:44:00', '2012-08-02 02:44:00', '<span style="color: #800000;">Question: Name one of the authors of <span class="bolditalic">In Search of Africa’s Great Tuskers</span></span>', ''),
(30, 'No', 'No', 'Competitions', 4, 'rod macleod', 'Wildside Mag Competition Winners - Autumn 2012', 'shargcave.jpg', '250', '', 'Congratulations to the lucky winners of competitions in the previous edition of Wildside.', '<span class="bold">Louise Tucker</span> wins accommodation for one person for two nights, one shark cage dive and an evening presentation and discussion on Oceans Research work by one of their scientists. The shark cage dive is in Mossel Bay and the stay is at the Oceans Campus, a three star hotel. We can’t wait to hear how you enjoy your unique prize. \r\n\r\n<span class="bold">Kevin Bestwick, Michelle Hibbert, Erwin Brandt, Paula Appelgryn and Tina Llabres</span> each win a copy of <span class="italic">The Last Rhinos by Lawrence Anthony</span>\r\n', '', '', '2012-08-02 03:09:00', '2012-08-02 03:09:00', '', ''),
(31, 'yes', 'No', 'Wildside-Warriors', 1, 'Dr Roelie Kloppers', 'Swaziland Hot Spot - From sugarcane to protected landscape', 'swaziland-debbie-cooper.jpg', '520', '', 'When most people think of Swaziland, they probably think of candle factories or of a monarchy that''s always in the news for Mugabian reasons, either buying a new private plane or throwing another lavish party. It’s a real pity that the monarch’s glamourous lifestyle dominates news from Swaziland. Not to say these stories aren’t entertaining, but it’s always better to get good news and that’s just what I found when I visited the country last month.\r\n', 'The landscape of this small landlocked country in Southern Africa is almost completely dominated by vast sugarcane plantations. In fact, sugar is the base of the economy of Swaziland, employing nearly35% of the workforce. Softdrinks is one of the primary exports of Swaziland and most of the country’s trade (90%) is with South Africa. \r\n<br/><br/>\r\nWhile driving through the sugarcaned landscape I kept searching for remnants of un-transformed bushveld areas. Driving northwards from the Golela border post the first sign of inspiration is the new Royal Jozini Big 6 Reserve. Here, a group of visionary businessmen and conservationists are returning degraded cattle lands around Lake Jozini to pristine bushveld. The area is now fenced and a modest amount of game has returned. It should eventually link to the Pongola Nature Reserve in South Africa as part of a Transfrontier Conservation Initiative. In South Africa this could include the Zululand Conservation Corridor and run as far south as Phinda, but let me stick to the Swaziland story for now! A few kilometers north of Royal Jozini communities along the Lubombo Mountains are also trying their hand at brining areas under conservation and establishing Eco-tourism ventures. \r\n<br/><br/>\r\nFurther north along the Lubombo Mountains lies Swaziland’s largest conservation areas – Hlane Royal National Park and Mlawula.These reserves have also been earmarked to form part of a Transfrontier Initiative – in this case linking with a conservation area in Mozambique.\r\n<br/><br/>\r\nWhen I visited Swaziland last month I met with a group of visionary conservationist who feel it would be possible to create a conservation corridor that would link all these areas on the eastern side of of the country into a mega- protected landscape. As crazy as this may seem, it just might work and it would also link three Transfrontier Parks thus establishing a mega-reserve,linking the Lubombo Mountains and the Indian Ocean! This remains long-term planning – for now the aim is to create a Protected Landscape along the Lubombo Mountains. \r\n\r\n<br/><br/>These Mountains are home to some of the rarest cycads and other endemic flora, yet are not protected in any of the three countries for which the Mountains form a natural border. We have been able to partner with our group of visionaries, and this is the first grant ever of the Critical Ecosystem Partnership Fund in Swaziland. I am going to visit the area various times over the next three years and will report on progress made in acheiving a considerable conservation impact in southern Africa. Good luck to  all involved!\r\n\r\n<p><a title="Wildlands Conservation Trust" href="http://www.wildlands.co.za" target="_blank" style="color:red;">www.wildlands.co.za</a></p>\r\n\r\n', '', '', '2012-08-28 10:55:00', '2012-08-28 10:55:00', '', ''),
(32, 'yes', 'yes', 'Wildside-Warriors', 1, 'Lisa Kohler', 'Kirsten Dukes, South Africa’s ‘Miss Earth’ ambassador, becomes a Wildside Warrior', 'kirsty-rhino-warrior-shirt-lare_full.jpg', '520', '', 'Accompanying the Wildside team to Nambiti Private Game Reserve is the beautiful Kirsten Dukes, South Africa’s ‘Miss Earth’ ambassador.', 'Kirsten has a deep passion for conservation, especially for the preservation of endangered species such as rhino. Kirsten joined Wildside as a guest of Wildside Warriors in support of Project Rhino KZN.\r\nMiss Earth South Africa is a programme that aims to provide young South African women the platform for making a sustainable difference in combatting the destruction of our natural heritage. The event helps create awareness of our environment, wildlife and the conservation of our natural legacy in South Africa, and ultimately the preservation of Mother Earth.\r\n\r\n<a title="Miss Earth SA" href="http://www.missearthsa.co.za" target="_blank" style="color:red;">Miss Earth SA</a></p>\r\n\r\n <img src="http://www.wildsidesa.co.za/admin/upload/server/php/files/kirsty-rhino-warrior-shirt.jpg" alt=""  width="520"/>', '', '', '2012-09-01 17:44:00', '2012-09-01 17:44:00', 'The Wildside team and Kirsten Dukes, South Africa’s ‘Miss Earth’ ambassador, encounter the most endangered large cat in africa – the cheetah (below). Photographs of Kirsten by Jessica Moya.', ''),
(34, 'yes', 'no', 'News', 0, 'Rod MacLeod', 'Orphaned by Poaching – These Baby Rhino''s Need Your Help.', 'Valentino-3.jpg', '520', '', 'Wildlifevets.com, is a wildlife veterinary practise in Mpumalanga,  who are passionate about rhino. They are raising baby rhinos at their own expense that have been orphaned by poaching. They feed the babies Lactogen 2, a Nestlé product. Lactogen 2, contains just the right ingredients that are not too fatty for their systems. Wildlifevets are seeking donors as the amounts to feed babies are staggering.', 'Nestlé, a multinational consortium and one of the biggest suppliers of baby food products to the African continent – have declined to help, sighting lack of budget as their reason. If you know of anyone who is influential at Nestlé and who might be able to find funds for such a noteworthy cause then help us make them aware of these baby rhino''s in need.\r\n\r\nIf any readers want to assist they can contact Michelle Raath directly.\r\n\r\nMichelle Raath – admin@wildlifevets.com', '', '', '2012-09-16 22:00:00', '2012-09-16 22:00:00', '<a href="http://www.wildlifevets.com" target="_blank">www.wildlifevets.com</a>', ''),
(35, 'No', 'No', 'Competitions', 0, '', 'Win one of 4 stylish, packable, crushable Emthunzini Hats', 'hat.jpg', '', '', 'Everyone would like a packable, stylish hat to take on holiday, for either the beach or the bushveld. Our beautiful, but harsh sun means that South Africans are four times more likely to develop skin cancer than any other form of cancer. Four lucky Wildside readers can win UPF50+, fashionable, crushable and adjustable Oscar panama-style hats from Emthunzini Hats.', 'With an Emthunzini Hat, it’s fashionably fun to protect your face and neck, as every hat meets with the International UPF 50+ requirements.\r\n\r\nThis means that over 98% of the sun’s harmful ultraviolet rays are blocked out. All Emthunzini Hats carry the Cancer Association of South Africa (CANSA) Seal of Recognition and have the UPF50+ swing ticket. They also endorsed by the Skin and Cancer Foundation for Australia. The hats are crushable, perfect for packing and backpacks; have a hidden drawstring so can be customized to fit; look stylish and there are 20 styles that combine familiar favourites with global trendy designs. Colours range from pale pastels to bright electrics and styles includes unisex styles, and hats specifically for men, women and children.\r\n\r\n<span class"bold">A percentage of sales is donated to www.xpsociety.co.za caring for South Africans born with a rare genetic disease that leads to skin cancer in childhood, which if undiagnosed and untreated, can be fatal. This disease is known as Xeroderma Pigmentosum.</span>\r\n\r\nFor information and to order visit www.sunhats.co.za or call 022 409 2160.\r\n\r\nEmail gilly@sunhats.co.za.', 'Enter Competition', '', '2012-09-30 00:23:00', '2012-09-30 00:23:00', '<span style="color: #800000;">Question: Where are these hats made</span>', ''),
